This is such a good one! I was intimidated by the length of it at first, but so glad I did it. I'm doing the Breath series now, day 8! But wanted to finish up Revolution along side it, as I had not quite finished before Breath started. Thank you for honoring all walks of life, especially for Elephant pose. I have moderate scoliosis, but have always had a very strong back and things, and especially good flexibility thanks to yoga. 

I've always struggled with core strength and strength in my glutes as well as hip flexibility. Even when I was very active, going to the gym and practicing yoga every day.

Since the p^andemic started, I was laid off from my very active job (I was a nanny and also walked to and from work). I've also become more depressed and just lacked motivation. I got back into yoga finally last month. This is the first time ever in my life (I'm 30) that I've been able to activate my core and my pelvic floor. In addition to the scoliosis (which has gotten worse since the pandemic) I have a very weak pelvic floor from a traumatic childbirth experience. My pain and tightness have made me slow down and be PATIENT. I'm using muscles I never have before. I realize now that I CAN engage my side abs while breathing deeply into my belly.

Its like I've peeled back a new layer. Thank you.

hey, adriene, can you tell me something?  I've been practicing with you since May 2020 everyday (sometimes multiple times a day to shake off my negative head space) and my hamstrings do not seem to be loosening up! I'm sure you probably won't read this since the video is old, but I had to say something. I found this video really frustrating. I know you don't like to show alternatives with straps and blocks, but when you do this many poses that are going to be completely impossible for someone who has any sort of belly, it makes me feel crappy and like my body is the problem. for you to be like "oh hey, here's a wild alternative to lizard" but for you to not be like "Some of you will not be able to reach your toes/grab your leg/hook your elbow, and here are adjustments you can make" felt really shitty. as a fat woman it was really hard and sad. i was not sure if the problem was me, but my friend who is also fat had the same experience doing this video, too. still love these videos and i'm grateful for them, but i wish you were more considerate of how some people need to make accessibility adjustments, and helped us feel ok about them and gave good ideas.
